  <main class="page-main">
    <h1 class="page-title">Relativistic jets</h1>

    <div class="infobox">
      <h3 class="infobox-title">Relativistic jets</h3>
      <table>
        <tr><th>Type:</th><td>Concept</td></tr>
        <tr><th>Educational level:</th><td>Intermediate</td></tr>
        <tr><th>Key Papers:</th><td>Tchekhovskoy et al.; Perrucho et al.</td></tr>
      </table>
    </div>

    <p><strong>Relativistic jets</strong> are jets whose bulk flow speeds approach the speed of light (Lorentz factor gamma >> 1). They require relativistic hydrodynamics or MHD for accurate description and show different shock and acceleration behaviours compared to sub-relativistic jets.</p>

    <h2>Why distinguish?</h2>
    <p>Relativistic shocks are often less efficient for standard DSA (because of anisotropic particle distributions and rapid escape). Peretti et al. (2603.16647) focus on sub-relativistic jets where standing recollimation shocks can be long-lived and efficient accelerators; relativistic generalizations are suggested as future work.</p>

